{"name":"Allegories, Anecdotes, Paradoxes, Dillemas","id":164,"content":"<div class=\"box1\">\n<p><strong>Allegory:</strong> a story, poem, or picture that can be interpreted to reveal a hidden meaning, typically a moral or political one.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Parable:</strong>&nbsp;a simple story used to illustrate a moral or spiritual lesson.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Anecdote:</strong>&nbsp;a short amusing or interesting story about a real incident or person.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Paradox:</strong>&nbsp;a seemingly absurd or contradictory statement or proposition which when investigated may prove to be well founded or true.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Dilemma:</strong>&nbsp;a situation in which a difficult choice has to be made between two or more alternatives, especially ones that are equally undesirable.</p>\n\n<p><em><span style=\"color:#8e44ad;\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Stories have been used throughout the history of mankind to convey messages, to motivate/guide people; sometimes they don&#39;t seem to have tautological reasoning, sometimes they lead to absurdities, but there&#39;s no denying that they are powerful.</span></span></em></p>\n</div>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?q=chinese+farmer+horse+story&amp;oq=chinese+farmer+horse+story\" target=\"_blank\">Chinese Farmer and his Horse Story</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; The worldly events can take unexpected turns in positive as well as negative directions, being overwhelmed by them does not do any good.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lady,_or_the_Tiger%3F\" target=\"_blank\">The Lady And The Tiger</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free-rider_problem\" target=\"_blank\">Free Rider Problem</a> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newcomb%27s_paradox\" target=\"_blank\">,The Newbomb&#39;s Dillema</a>&nbsp; <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kavka%27s_toxin_puzzle\" target=\"_blank\">Toxin Dillema</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Sometimes it&#39;s just hard to make a rational decision.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Innocent_prisoner%27s_dilemma\" target=\"_blank\">Innocent Prisoner&#39;s Dillema</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Sometimes people maintain their position of innocence even though it is more useful to just admit guilt.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prisoner%27s_dilemma\" target=\"_blank\">The Prisoner&#39;s Dillema</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Sometimes we take decisions (due to limited view of the overall context) which prove to be not the best decision if we had all the data, and were looking from a higher perspective.</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abilene_paradox\" target=\"_blank\">Abilene paradox</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Sometimes, as a group we settle (agree) on a decision, which none (or most) of the individuals of the group actually favour. Basically because all the members are not explicit about their opinions.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simpson%27s_paradox\" target=\"_blank\">Simpson&#39;s Paradox</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;Sometimes, even data can lead us to wrong conclusions.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suicide_(book)\" target=\"_blank\">Durkheim&#39;s Suicide</a></p>\n\n<p>Is participating in military suicide?</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304032257_The_Bell_Curve_Revisited_Testing_Controversial_Hypotheses_with_Molecular_Genetic_Data\" target=\"_blank\">The Bell Curve Revisited</a></p>\n\n<p>Sometimes, our scientific methods mislead us to wrong conclusions about society.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ship_of_Theseus_(film)\" target=\"_blank\">Ship Of Theseus</a></p>\n\n<p>It&#39;s extremely hard to determine when one thing changes and becomes another thing.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q4pDUxth5fQ&amp;list=PLJicmE8fK0EjW2AVwcSc4NvGyJJaw7bzh&amp;index=16\" target=\"_blank\">The Myth of Sisyphus</a></p>\n\n<p>Raises question about our meaningless existence.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allegory_of_the_cave\" target=\"_blank\">Allegory Of The Cave</a></p>\n\n<p>Raises questions about the nature of reality, and how less people are willing to step outside to see the bigger picture. How men are prisoners in a mental cave.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_of_Gyges\">Ring Of Gyges</a></p>\n\n<p>If it is ensured that a man will never get discovered for his actions, will a man choose to act just? What does it tell about the nature of justice, and of men in general?</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ashidakim.com/zenkoans/zenindex.html\" target=\"_blank\">101 Zen Koans</a></p>\n\n<p>Zen Koans were developed for the monks to meditate. There is no single interpretation of any of these Koans, and probably that was the whole purpose, to realise that there&#39;s no certainty. &nbsp;These Koans also make us realise that there&#39;s always more than what meets the eye.</p>\n\n<p>Some of the Koans are in the form of questions, others in form of parables.</p>\n\n<p>&quot;If a tree falls in the forest and no one is around to hear, does it make a sound?&quot;</p>\n\n<p>&quot;Is the glass half full or half empty?&quot;</p>\n\n<p><em>Note, there can always be a third (or yet another) way to look at the things.</em></p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><a href=\"http://www.ashidakim.com/zenkoans/4obedience.html\" target=\"_blank\">Obedience Koan:</a>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#4e5f70;\">How did the master play his trick?</span> - Master&nbsp;knew that the man will do anything to prove his point, he was so full of passion and jealousy. Also, maybe just like his own high ego, the man projected the same egotism&nbsp;onto master and thought that the master would try to make him do something big.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#4e5f70;\">Is there any hidden message?</span> - Sometimes, or most of the times, you do not realise that you are presided/domineered/governed by others.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Puzzles &amp; Riddles:</h2>\n\n<p>From the book <a href=\"https://archive.org/stream/WhatIsTheNameOfThisBook/What-is-the-Name-of-this-Book_djvu.txt\" target=\"_blank\">&#39;What Is The Name Of This Book&#39;</a>:</p>\n\n<pre>\n4. Whose Picture Am I Looking At? - </pre>\n\n<p>[With some tools of logic, we can come up with solutions for this; What about the person who first solved it mentally? What sort of mental tools did he use?]</p>\n\n<pre>\n6 What Happens If an Irresistible Cannonball Hits \nan Immovable Post?</pre>\n\n<p>[What do such questions tell us? Are the questions invalid? Or, do they tell us about limits of logic?]</p>\n\n<pre>\n7  &bull; Red Blue Socks </pre>\n\n<p>[What does this tell us? We see big numbers and forget the fundamentals.]</p>\n\n<pre>\n10 &bull; Who Was the Murderer? </pre>\n\n<p>[Does the intention matter?]</p>\n\n<pre>\n12. Two Indians.</pre>\n\n<p>[What&#39;s the catch here? The word &#39;big&#39; leads your mind to a male identity]</p>\n\n<pre>\n13. The Clock That Stopped. </pre>\n\n<p>[How to solve a problem in abstract form]</p>\n\n<p>Monkey tricks 15-24</p>\n\n<p>[These monkey tricks show us that perception matters. That when you see something strange, absurd, take a step back to see whether you are being fooled.]</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Sources:&nbsp;https://www.paradoxparkway.com/paradoxes/</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"philosophy","tags":null,"img":null,"summary":null,"lastUpdated":"2020-04-26T04:21:53.479+0000"}